Intellectual Merit: The ICAD Doctoral Consortium was designed to advance knowledge and understanding across the fields as well as within the field. Students presented their on-going research with both theoretical frameworks and practical applications.

-        advancing understanding and novel discovery of auditory displays and sonification;

-        providing an interdisciplinary atmosphere that spanned the areas of diversity critical to ICAD;

-        obtaining distribution channels to reach the diverse fields and convincing researchers in the various fields to come and share their expertise;

-        promoting scholarship and networking among new researchers in this emerging interdisciplinary area;



Broader Impacts: The successful implementation of the Doctoral Consortium at ICAD 2018 conference has a number of crucial broader impacts.

-        New inspiration and networking opportunities were provided to young researchers and domain experts;

-        Students' research projects were disseminated via posters during the ICAD 2018 technical program;

-        The interchange of ideas and opinions on the applications of auditory displays and sonification will facilitate science, technology, engineering, and mathematics (STEM) education;

-        ThinkTank will likely increase partnerships between academia, industry, government, and others;

-        The outcomes out of the ThinkTank and ICAD conference provided data, models, and systems which visually impaired people could benefit from. This inclusive design approach will also impact people with other disabilities and eventually help them live more independently.   



Outcomes:

"ThinkTank", Doctoral Consortium at ICAD 2018 was very successful. In total 29 participants attended the event. There were 11 students (five female students, one undergraduate student, and one blind student) who presented their work across different application domains. Student presenters had diverse backgrounds, including music technology, psychology and human factors, computer science, climate changes, human-centered design, etc. This year, specifically there were an undergrad student presenter and observers. There were eight panel members (six from academia, one from the government, and one from industry). In addition, there were 10 observers, composed of students and faculty. This is a huge success given that this is a pre-conference event and they did not need to come. Participants had a deep discussion on experimental design, sonification mappings, context, interaction, available technologies, research directions, etc. with the international panel members. The presentations given at ThinkTank are as follows:

-        "Non-biometric verbal authentication for voice interfaces"

-        "Across sensory modalities: the effectiveness of cross-sensory representations"

-        "Affective interactive dancer sonification II"

-        "Representing twitter users' engagement by sonification"

-        "Data-embedded audio synthesis with multiple degrees of freedom in musical expressiveness"

-        "Conversational sonification: Exploring the intersection of data sonification, voice interfaces, and interactivity?

-        "Educator feedback and evaluation of sonified STEM educational tools for blind students"

-        "Investigations in the construction of and listener response to artful data sonifications of Arctic climate change"

-        "Perceptions of a spatialized acoustic environment with immersive visual presentations"

-        "HoloDeck - Connecting artists"



After the presentation and discussion, student presenters and panels had small group discussions on further topics (e.g., career, sound implementation, networking and communication, etc.) in rotation. Student scholars' research projects were also presented via posters during the ICAD 2018 technical program. The ThinkTank chair and the conference chair prepared for a short survey to assess the ThinkTank program, which included a Likert-type scale (1 Not at all, 5 Very much). The participants rated 4.42 to the question, "How satisfied are you with the student presentations?", 4.15 to "How satisfied are you with the Q&amp;A and discussions?", 3.84 to "How satisfied are you with the roundtable on research and career strategies?", 4.36 to "How active was the communication among presenters, panelists, and in-room discussants?" and 4.47 to "Rate the overall quality of the ThinkTank workshop" (1 Very Poor - 5 Very Good). The last question asked participants to describe their impressions/thoughts/suggestions for the future Student ThinkTank. There were considerable positive comments (e.g., "very supportive and constructive environment to share research ideas, work in progress", "diversity of student presenters", "the main ThinkTank presentations provided me with lots of great feedback", "A great practice to know what people are doing in sonification from various background, in completely different fields", "It's so helpful to have a workshop space for unfinished work in progress + to get feedback". There were also suggestions for improvements (e.g., "would be nice to have even more discussion time", "I recommend holding strict time limits so there is time for discussion", "I would have liked to get a bit more information about the participants beforehand". Most improvement ideas were about the need for more discussion and we could consider balancing the two more properly in the next iteration. Overall, the ThinkTank event was successful with many and various participants. As the survey showed, the participants were highly satisfied with the presentations and discussions as a whole and took their lessons from the event.





